<br>
Math is the way to approach it, you are quite correct. But when we speak of Basic Strategy we speak of a simple, predetermined set of rules, not of some uh -- strategy. Basic Strategy is a set of simple rules: stand on 12 on 4, 5, 6, stand on 13 for 2, 3, and on 17 for 7 or above. Split 8s and A, always. Never split 10s. Etc. <br>
<br>
There are several &quot;layers&quot; of Basic Strategy. You got your hard hit, soft hit, double down, split, insurance, whatnot. Knowing Basic Strategy means you never take insurance, unless you've been following the count -- is the deck hot? Is the deck hot? Do you feel lucky, punk? Most people don't even know. 99.9% of Blackjack players don't care, they make their insurance decision based on hunches. <br>
<br>
That's why casinos win. <br>
<br>
I don't play Blackjack no more, but I used to play, and kept to the basic Strategy. It didn't earn me any money, but I never lost too much either. And I am the kinda guy who actually remembers how much I lose -- and most often forgets how much I win, heheh. <br>
